### **4. Detailed Statistical Analysis**

#### üìà **Partisan Asymmetry in Political Discourse**
The most statistically robust finding is the deep rhetorical divide between parties. ANOVA tests confirm that Republican-authored documents score significantly higher on both populism and nationalism.

**ANOVA: Populism-Pluralism Score by Party**
| Party | N | Mean Populism | F-Statistic | p-value | Significance |
| :--- | :-: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Democrat | 27 | 0.721 | \multirow{2}{*}{6.43} | \multirow{2}{*}{**0.015**} | \multirow{2}{*}{‚≠ê **Significant**} |
| Republican | 15 | 0.817 | | | |

**ANOVA: Nationalism-Patriotism Score by Party**
| Party | N | Mean Nationalism | F-Statistic | p-value | Significance |
| :--- | :-: | :--- | :--- | :--- | \multirow{2}{*}{‚≠ê **Significant**} |
| Democrat | 27 | 0.686 | \multirow{2}{*}{10.33} | \multirow{2}{*}{**0.003**} |
| Republican | 15 | 0.789 | | | |

This quantitative divide is illustrated by the curated evidence. Republican discourse frequently employs direct, anti-establishment populist framing, portraying a corrupt capital elite betraying "the people" [5], and pairs this with powerful nationalist slogans [1, 6]. While Democratic rhetoric also utilizes populist themes, such as critiques of economic inequality [2], it often frames them within narratives of meritocracy and civic opportunity [4], resulting in lower average scores.

#### **üìä Distribution of Rhetorical Styles**
The derived metrics show a corpus skewed heavily toward populist rhetoric and away from institutionalism.

