This distribution indicates that `Liberal Democratic` discourse (low populism, low nationalism) is rare in the analyzed corpus of high-stakes political communication.

#### **üîó The Strong Coupling of Populism and Nationalism**
The analysis explicitly refutes the hypothesis of rhetorical decoupling (H4). The Pearson correlation between the two primary axes is extremely high, demonstrating a powerful symbiosis.

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Populism-Pluralism Score] -- "r = 0.799 (Strongly Correlated)" --> B[Nationalism-Patriotism Score]
    style A fill:#ffcdd2,stroke:#c62828
    style B fill:#ffcdd2,stroke:#c62828
```

This strong link suggests that, in this corpus, appeals to "the people" against elites are frequently interwoven with appeals to a specific vision of national greatness and cultural identity. The prevalence of "Ethno-Populist" classifications in the data further supports this. The framework's ability to measure both high scores simultaneously, avoiding the "Bolsonaro Problem," was critical to uncovering this pattern.

#### **ü§µ Presidential Rhetorical Signatures**
Hypothesis H5 was strongly supported. Presidents exhibit remarkably consistent rhetorical styles across different speeches within their administrations.

| President | Populism `std` | Nationalism `std` | Consistency |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Donald Trump | **0.036** | **0.039** | ‚úÖ **Very High** |
